metadata.name: Linetract #27
metadata.description:
Art unites people, the same is also true with Artists.

"Linetract" is a collaborative work of two different artist: @Jolie__Michel and @Uniray_net 
Different backgrounds, different styles, same passion for creativity and Art!

"Linetract" is an abstract composition of simple shapes forms and colors, merged into a final minimal and hopefully aesthetic interesting result :)

CONTROLS

KEYS:

- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

Made with p5js and custom shaders

Collaboration project by @Jolie__Michel and @Uniray_net
© January 2023

metadata.name: Geo-forest #3dart #17
metadata.description:
3D art - geometric forest

Jagel Geometry is a 3D collection that I designed with Trendy Max software
I have modeled all the flowers and plants and 3D forms myself!
(Because of my interest in 3D modeling and it is my second field of work)
I have rendered with materials that show the corners of the lines more
And I have created a forest by combining layers
inside which there are geometric forms
This work has 8 layers
Two layers of background and frame
4 layers of flowers and plants
A layer of geometric forms
and a layer of special forms of flowers and plants

I hope you like it!

metadata.name: Ephemeral Fountain v1.0 #53
metadata.description:
This project originated with me thinking about how to do very realistic glass spheres that can be manipulated and moved within the THREE.js environment. Mixing that with several hundred ephemeral non-glass objects which are moving in a fountain-like flow, adding reflection and refraction to the glass, and combining it all in a physical existence which I playfully only impose on the non-glass objects nearby... in this world, glass can move through glass, with interesting effects similar to diamonds firing when light hits them at just the right angle! 

Extremely rare to get 8 glass spheres... By the randomness imposed, 30% will have one sphere, 30% two, 20% three, 10% four, 5% five, 3% six, 1% seven and 1% eight. Happy hunting!

metadata.name: Illusion City #105
metadata.description:
Illusion City reflects the variety of Istanbul by its different and divergent zones, day and night, humid summers and ice cold winters, colorful neighborhoods and giant plazas, its never ending human and vehicle traffic.

This series is an expression of how we experience this city, kind of like a love and hate relationship. The city that is a cradle of civilizations now has become a concrete jungle. Our beautiful city and its citizens are now trying to find their own balance in this state of chaos.

We wanted to express these complex emotions with a long-form generative artwork since it is the most suitable medium to explore every possible combination of emotions we have about our city. 

Best experienced in full screen.

Probabilities;

- 3 pre-made color palettes, 1 generative color palette

- 3 blend modes

- 3 topping placements

- 8 different particle angle compositions

- Several grid sizes and edges

- An intentionally kept in glitch (rare)

In live mode, press ‘s’ to save as .png (2000 x 2666 px )

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, July 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: September #121
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
